{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1168"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1168"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.1,0.21,0.05,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83167"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1168"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28462"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83167"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman is being assessed for a laparoscopic para-oesophageal hernia repair. She has type II diabetes requiring metformin as well as hypertension for which she takes candesartan. At the age of 42, she was treated for breast cancer and is now disease-free.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her BMI is 24 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, and heart rate is 80/min. The remainder of her physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following risk factors puts this patient at the highest risk of developing a venous thromboembolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignancy history","Hypertension","Diabetes","BMI","Age"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Caprini Score for Venous Thromboembolism is a widely used tool to assess the risk of VTE in surgical patients. It assigns points to various risk factors, with a history of \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignancy\u003C/strong\u003E being a significant contributor. This patient\u0027s history of breast cancer, despite being disease-free, still places her at a higher risk for VTE compared to other factors. The Caprini Score is particularly relevant in this context as it helps clinicians stratify patients based on their risk and decide on appropriate prophylactic measures to prevent VTE, which is a common and potentially serious complication in surgical patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is a common condition but is not a major risk factor for VTE in the Caprini Score. It contributes less to the overall risk compared to a history of cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes\u003C/strong\u003E is also considered in risk assessments, but like hypertension, it is not as heavily weighted as a history of malignancy in the context of VTE risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBMI\u003C/strong\u003E is a factor in the Caprini Score, with higher BMI values contributing to increased risk. However, this patient\u0027s BMI of 24 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E is within the normal range and does not significantly elevate her VTE risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge\u003C/strong\u003E is a factor in VTE risk, with older age contributing more points in the Caprini Score. However, at 59 years old, this patient\u0027s age contributes less to her VTE risk compared to her history of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Caprini Score for Venous Thromboembolism is a widely utilised and validated VTE risk assessment model for surgical patients.","A history of malignancy is a significant risk factor for venous thromboembolism in surgical patients.","Age, hypertension, diabetes, and BMI are also considered in VTE risk assessment but may carry less weight than a history of malignancy."],"references":["Hanh BM, Cuong LQ, Son NT, Duc DT, Hung TT, Hung DD, Giang TB, Hiep NH, Xuyen HTH, Nga NT, Chu DT. Determination of Risk Factors for Venous Thromboembolism by an Adapted Caprini Scoring System in Surgical Patients. J Pers Med. 2019 Jul 17;9(3):36. doi: 10.3390/jpm9030036. PMID: 31319527; PMCID: PMC6789529. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31319527/","Grant PJ, Greene MT, Chopra V, Bernstein SJ, Hofer TP, Flanders SA. Assessing the Caprini Score for Risk Assessment of Venous Thromboembolism in Hospitalized Medical Patients. Am J Med. 2016 May;129(5):528-535. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2015.10.027. Epub 2015 Nov 6. PMID: 26551977; PMCID: PMC5331485. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26551977/","Lee AY, Levine MN. Venous thromboembolism and cancer: risks and outcomes. Circulation. 2003 Jun 17;107(23 Suppl 1):I17-21. doi: 10.1161/01.CIR.0000078466.72504.AC. PMID: 12814981. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12814981/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1168"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-02T11:27:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-02T11:32:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1168"}}